          "body": "The psalm's final word is *yare'* — 'fear,' reverential awe, the creaturely posture before the holy God. The psalm began with a petition for grace and ends with a prophecy of universal reverence. The trajectory is certain: the same God who causes His face to shine on the covenant community will, through that community's blessed witness, draw 'all the ends of the earth' (*ephes ha-erets*, a phrase denoting the farthest extremity of the known world) into the posture of fear before Him. This is not the terror of the condemned but the awe of those who have encountered the just, guiding, gracious God of Israel and have nowhere else to go but before Him. The New Testament reads this trajectory as fulfilled and being fulfilled in the gospel's global advance (Romans 15:9-12, where Paul strings together four Old Testament texts about Gentile praise, including the Psalms) and will reach its completion only at the eschaton (Revelation 15:3-4: 'All the nations will come and worship before You'). Psalm 67 is not merely a harvest hymn. It is the entire biblical theology of mission compressed into seven verses."
