        "title": "Grace requested for a missionary purpose — the Aaronic premise and its 'that'",
        "range": "67:1-2",
        "excerpt": "God be gracious to us and bless us, and cause His face to shine upon us — that Your way may be known on the earth, Your salvation among all nations.",
        "body": "The psalm's opening verse is almost verbatim from Numbers 6:24-26, the Aaronic benediction prescribed for the Mosaic priesthood over Israel. The psalmist has not merely borrowed devotional language; he has theologized the borrowing. By attaching a purpose clause ('that Your way may be known,' v.2) to the priestly blessing, he reveals what the Aaronic blessing was always meant to produce. Grace given to Israel was never an end in itself — it was the upstream cause of a downstream effect: the knowledge of God's character and salvific activity spreading to all nations.\n\nThe word translated 'salvation' (*yeshuah*) carries the full weight of covenantal rescue — deliverance from enemies, from sin's consequences, from the chaos that threats to unravel the created order. Paired with 'Your way' (*derekh*, God's characteristic manner of acting), the verse presents a twofold revelation: God's moral character (how He acts) and God's redemptive act (what He does for the helpless). Both are to be known 'on the earth' — *erets*, the whole inhabited world, not merely Palestine.\n\nThe Abrahamic covenant is the deep background. Genesis 12:2-3 structured blessing the same way: 'I will bless you... and in you all the families of the earth will be blessed.' The psalmist is not innovating; he is praying the Abrahamic promise back to the God who made it. Calvin saw in this verse the proper posture of the visible church in every generation — to receive grace not as private property but as missionary capital, asking God's favor because the world is watching and the knowledge of God travels through the blessed community's witness.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chanan* (be gracious) — unmerited favor extended to the inferior. *Barakh* (bless) — to endow with fruitfulness. *Paneh* (face) — the personal, directed presence of God, not an abstract influence. *Yeshuah* (salvation) shares its root with the name Yeshua (Jesus) — the psalmist prays for the nations to know the very thing the New Testament will announce as embodied in a person."
